Environment Variables:

Should set all the environment variables for staging and production environment. If any environment variable is not set the default value is used.
NODE_ENV(production|staging|local) default local
LEXSTEP_URL  default http://localhost:8080
LEXSTEP_DB_PORT default 3306
LEXSTEP_DB_NAME default lateralme
LEXSTEP_DB_HOST default localhost
LEXSTEP_DB_USER default root
LEXSTEP_DB_PASSSWORD default '' (empty string)

Client App

To start or build client app first do

cd square/client/

npm start

Runs the app in development mode.
Open http://localhost:3000 to view it in the browser.

npm run build

build the app for production in client/dist folder.

Server App

to start the server app first do
cd square/

npm start

starts the server app. Weekly subscribtion emails will be only enabled if NODE_ENV="production".

npm run maintenace

start the app in maintenance mode. It just servers the site maintenance page

CONFIGURATION OF ABRAAJ POC
 
Following are the steps you need to follow in order to configure your remote server once you connect to your server using PUTTY:
INSTALLING PRE-REQUISITS
  1. Install python v2.7.9 using apt-get command.
  2. Run command “python”, if it displays version of python then python is properly installed.
  3. Install Node.js if not already installed.
  4. Install Ruby and gems.
  5. Install Compass.
 
 
INSTALLING GRUNT AND BOWER
  1. Run the command "npm install –g grunt-cli” to install grunt-cli.
  2. “Sudo npm install –g bower” to install bower.
 
RUNNING APPLICATION
  1. Unzip the attached folder on your remote server.
  2. Open a new Screen using command “screen” and the pressing ENTER twice.
  3. Once done, go to lexhire/square/routes and run the command “sudo npm install” and then do the same in lexhire/square/client
  4. And then run the command “bower install” in lexhire/square/
  5. Once all the packages finish to install, run the command “npm run server" in lexhire/square/routes

Once server is up, hide the opened screen by pressing CTRL + A + D.
Do not forget to open the port 8080 in the security group on AWS console.

Follow the following steps to Block an IP on Lexstep

1. Edit file /square/routes/blockedIP.json
2. Add the IP to block in JSON i.e "127.0.0.1"
3. Push changes
4. Restart server for it to take effect.

> Restoring/Using AMI Backup
  1. Open AMI List.
    • https://eu-west-1.console.aws.amazon.com/ec2/v2/home?region=eu-west-1#Images:sort=name
  2. select instance. then click actions, and click launch.
    • This will open an Instance launching wizard.
  3. Choose an instance type and click "next configuration" button.
  4. Configure the Instance details (if have to else will be picked from the saved ones). and press "Add storage" button.
  5. add new volumes if have to, by default the AMI valume will be included. Press "Add Tags" button.
  6. On the "Add Tags" page,
    • click "add Tag" button.
      • add tag's key and value and press "configure security group button".
  7. On "Configure Security Group"
    • choose "Select an existing security group" option. and select the desired security group. then press "Review and Launch" button.
  8. Review the settings and press "launch" button.
  9. Next choose the private key to connect to the instance using SSH.
    • select "choose an existing key" option. to use the same key as old instance. and press "Launch Instance"​​​​
  10. A success message is displayed saying your instance is created.
    • Scroll down to click on the "View instances" button.
  11. The newly created instance can be seen in the Instances list.

forever script is being used for running node server. It is used to persist all node logs and ensure auto restart of server in case of crash. More information can be found on https://github.com/foreverjs/forever

Navigate to node file and use the following commands to manipulate node server using forever:
  1. install node modules in "client/ " and "route/"
    • sudo npm install
  2. create dist foilder
    • Go to client/
    • run "sudo npm run build" or for live build server "sudo  npm start"
  3. Start Node server
    1. Go to routes/
    2. For staritng local server
      • run => npm start​​​​​
    3. For staring staging
      • ​​​​​​​​​​​​​​run => sudo forever start -c "npm run staging-server"​​​​​​​​​​​​​​​​​​​​​​​​​​​​
    4. For starting production​​​​​​​
      • run => sudo forever start -c "npm run production-server"​​​​​​​​​​​​​​​​​​​​​
  4. Stop Node server
    • sudo forever stopall
  5.  View running forever scripts
    • sudo forever list

Log file:
A new log file is being made everytime forever script is run. Name of this file usually consists of 4 alphanumeric characters.
Log file can be found in following locations:

Staging/Prod: /home/bitnami/.forever
Local: C:/Users/name/.forever

> Creating Backup for the production before build:

NOTE: look for red lines in the images
  1. Open Ec2 instance list:
    • https://eu-west-1.console.aws.amazon.com/ec2/v2/home?region=eu-west-1#Instances:sort=instanceId
  2. Right Click on the Instance (for which the backup is to be created).
  3. Select "Create Image" option under the sub menu of "Image" in the right click menu.
    • This will open a pop up asking information about the image to be created
  4. Describe the image:
    • Enter details like "Name of the Image" and "description of the image being made".
    • Select "No reboot" option. so that instance doesnt reboot during the backup creation.
    • Un-select the "Delete on termination" option in the volume list row. so that once the instance is terminated, we still have the image of the Hard Disk of the instance.
    • click "create Image" button.
  5. This will initiate the backup process. The AMI will be created after some considerable time.
    • click "Close" button.
  6. The list of the images can be seen under the AMI option of the Ec2 Service.
  7. The backup of the image (specifically the "snapshot") can be found under "snapshots" menu of the Ec2 Service panel.
  8. Tag these newly created AMI and the snapshot:
    • Go to AMI list.
    • select the AMI.
    • In the "Tags" tab, add a new tag.
    • click "Save"
    • Do the same for Snapshot by going to Snapshots.
    • Select the snapshot.
    • In the "Tags" tab, add a new tag.
    • click "Save"
